node.text:
Saied Hussain has been hand making tiles out of cement for over 50 years. He says he’s one of the last still doing this work in Egypt — most other workshops couldn't withstand competition from marble and ceramic tiles. We went to Cairo to see how his business is still standing.

node.title: How one man in Egypt is keeping this 200-year-old tile tradition alive

node.text:
Bananas are facing a pandemic, too. Almost all of the bananas exported globally are just one variety called the Cavendish. 

The Cavendish is vulnerable to a fungus called Panama Disease, which is ravaging banana farms across the globe. If it's not stopped, the Cavendish may go extinct. 

We visited a farm in Colombia infected with Panama Disease and a lab in the Netherlands studying the fungus to see if biosecurity and breeding can save the $25 billion banana industry.

node.title: Why The World’s Most Popular Banana May Go Extinct

node.text:
Before they officially become Air Assault-qualified, all soldiers must graduate from a physically and mentally challenging course known as the Army’s "10 toughest days." Chief video correspondent Graham Flanagan spent four days inside The Sabalauski Air Assault School in the Fort Campbell Army Installation on the Tennessee-Kentucky border. According to the Army, Air Assault operations involve missions requiring the insertion and evacuation of personnel and equipment using assault helicopters.

The training is divided into three phases: combat assault, sling-load operations, and rappelling. But before phase one begins, all students must survive "day zero," which culminates with an obstacle course featuring two major events that all students must conquer — otherwise they are dropped from training before phase one begins.

node.title: How soldiers are trained in a course known as the Army's "10 toughest days"

node.text:
High-quality leather is synonymous with Italian fashion. Some of the most expensive leather is made through a process called vegetable tanning. It's a craft that has its origins in prehistory, and today the technique is kept alive in Tuscany. This time-consuming process can take weeks to produce a type of leather that becomes especially beautiful with age, all thanks to the use of naturally occurring vegetable tannins. While this method for making leather may be threatened by the world of fast fashion, its makers remain hopeful that genuine craftsmanship never goes out of style.

Peru has the world's highest death rate per capita from COVID-19. And the country's oxygen shortage is a large part of the problem.

Prices of medical oxygen have skyrocketed in places like Peru, Brazil, Mexico, and India as these countries confront deadly second waves of the virus. But without the infrastructure to combat the problem, many are left without a choice but to pay the price.

Silo Ridge is a luxurious gated community and private club in a rural area north of New York City.

Members like Weight Watchers CEO Mindy Grossman enjoy perks from swanky stables to gourmet meals.

node.text:
With US employers scrambling to fill open positions, job seekers have the power right now.

The unusual trend is allowing job hunters to be selective about their employers and seek organizations that align with their political views and demonstrate empathy and flexibility.

A job interview can be a crucial first insight into a company's culture and the best chance to learn whether a company will look after you.

Insider spoke with three career experts about the types of red flags job seekers should be on the lookout for.

node.text:
Retail sales are higher than before the pandemic, spurred by stimulus and pent-up demand.

Americans spent $621.3 billion at stores and restaurants last month, according to the Census Bureau. That's up 0.6% from the Bureau's revised estimate of $617.9 billion in May. Economists expected a 0.4% decline over the month, according to Bloomberg.

Americans seem to be getting ready to go out into the world more often. Spending at clothing stores increased 2.6% over the month to a seasonally-adjusted total of $25.8 billion, and spending at restaurants and bars rose 2.3% to $70.6 billion. As restaurants and bars continue to reopen and see expanded business, they are hiring hundreds of thousands of workers each month and raising pay.

Click the link in bio to read the full story by Andy Kiersz.

(Credit: Mark Ralston/AFP via Getty Images, The Census Bureau)

node.text:
Bananas are facing a pandemic, too. Almost all of the bananas exported globally are just one variety called the Cavendish. 

The Cavendish is vulnerable to a fungus called Panama Disease, which is ravaging banana farms across the globe. If it's not stopped, the Cavendish may go extinct. 

We visited a farm in Colombia infected with Panama Disease and a lab in the Netherlands studying the fungus to see if biosecurity and breeding can save the $25 billion banana industry.

It's easy for work emails to bleed into your personal life, but new data indicates the harm this can cause.

A study looked at the impact that consistently responding to emails out of established work hours can have on a person's health.

It found a correlation between responding out of hours and higher stress levels.

node.text:
Workers everywhere are quitting in droves.

But if you need to keep a job you don't like, there are ways to make sure it keeps you energized and growing.

Career-happiness coach Amy Nguyen asks her clients to list one to three things that they want to focus on each week, and then identify the accomplishment they'd be most proud of.

Read more tips in the story at the link in bio. 

Story by Shana Lebowitz.
 
(Credit: Rowan Jordan/Getty)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shows a woman sitting in front of her desk rubbing the bridge of her nose. It is overlaid with the headline which reads: "You've got to work. Here's how to be happy while doing it." There is an arrow indicating the ability to swipe through the post.

Large blue text on a black background reads: "Identify your strengths." Smaller white text underneath reads: "Many websites offer quizzes you can do to identify your strengths. As scary as it may sound, it's a good idea to ask your managers, colleagues, and even friends what your strengths are. Once you've got a lead on what you're uniquely good at, like project management or talent development, figure out how to tweak your job so it allows those skills to shine."

Large blue text on a black background reads: "Conduct an energy audit." Smaller white text underneath reads: "Psychotherapist and leadership coach Sarah Greenberg encourages anyone feeling stuck in this way to track how they feel while doing different tasks. Once you identify which tasks drain your energy, you might be able to enlist a colleague's help with the portion of a project you can't stand. You might also realize there are parts of your job that do engage you."

Large blue text on a black background reads: "Find opportunities to get better." Smaller white text underneath reads: "For example, look at team members you admire and consider what they do well and how you can cultivate those qualities. Keep in mind this is generally something you'll need to initiate yourself. Learning is 'the very thing you need in order to both get another position and stay engaged in your current job,' social psychologist Ron Friedman said."

Large blue text on a black background reads: "Remember this job isn't forever." Smaller white text underneath reads: "Even if it doesn't satisfy you, you can view it as a "bridge to the life and career you really want. After one of leadership coach and psychotherapist Sarah Greenberg's clients started viewing his job as a bridge, "it was just much easier for him to accept the current situation and feel pretty good about the sacrifices he was making at the time," she said.

node.text:
Call 2021 the "Great Summer Outdoors" — the result of a cultural shift that's taken place during the COVID-19 pandemic that encouraged even the al fresco averse to crack open the window a little.

It's no passing fad, either, especially among the wealthy.

Companies across the luxury market, whether providing services or products, report that the uptick in interest in outdoor pursuits meant a continued surge in spending.

Read more at the link in bio. 

Story by Mark Ellwood.
 
(Credit: Jeff Roberts, Kennebunkport Resort Collection, Gravity Haus, Fraser Y, OXO Outdoor)
